{{Orphan |date=December 2010}}

'''Desakota''' is a term used in [[urban geography]] used to describe areas in the extended surroundings of large cities, in which urban and agricultural forms of land use and settlement coexist and are intensively intermingled.

The term was coined by the urban researcher Terry McGee of the [[University of British Columbia]] around 1990. It comes from [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] ''desa'' "[[village]]" and kota "[[city]]".<ref>{{Citation |first=Stephen |last=Cairns |title=Troubling Real-estate: Reflecting on Urban Form in Southeast Asia |work=Critical Reflections on Cities in Southeast Asia |year=2002 |page=117}}</ref> Desakota areas typically occur in Asia, especially [[South East Asia]]. Examples can be found in the urbanised regions of [[Java]],<ref>{{Citation |first=Terry G. |last=McGee |title=Reconstructing ›The Southeast Asian City‹ in an Era of Volatile Globalization |work=Critical Reflections on Cities in Southeast Asia |year=2002 |pages=33–34}}</ref> the densely populated, delta-shaped areas on the peripheries of the [[Jakarta]] agglomeration ("[[Jabodetabek]]"), but also the extended metropolitan regions of [[Bangkok]] or [[Manila]].<ref>{{Citation |author=McGee |title=Reconstructing ›The Southeast Asian City‹ |year=2002 |pages=47–48}}</ref>

Desakota areas are situated outside the periurban zones, from which daily commuting is easily possible, i.e. more than 30 or 50&nbsp;km off the city centre. They often sprawl alongside arterial and communication roads, sometimes from one agglomeration to the next. They are characterised by high population density and intensive agricultural use (especially [[Paddy field|wet-rice cultivation]]), but differ from densely populated rural areas by more urban-like characteristics.<ref>{{Citation |author=McGee |title=The Emergence of ''Desakota'' Regions in Asia. |year=1991 |pages=6–7}}</ref> These criteria are: developed transport networks, high population mobility, increasing activity outside the agricultural sector, the coexistence of many different forms of land use, more female participation in paid labour, and unregulated land use.<ref>{{Citation |last1=Chia |first1=Lin Sien |first2=Martin |last2=Perry |title=Introduction |work=Southeast Asia Transformed: A Geography of Change |publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies |place=Singapur |year=2003 |isbn=981-230-119-4 |page=12}}</ref>

Given their rambling extent and indistinct boundaries, the emergence of Desakota regions brings difficulties for the administration, as uniform plans, regulations or designs are hardly viable. Desakota regions are characterised by high mobility of goods and services and rapid change in patterns of settlement. They usually elude the division in functually specialised zones that is conventionally applied in urban geography. Completely different forms of use, as e.g. traditional agriculture, large scale and cottage industry, amusement parks and golf courses, shopping centres and retail parks, and forms of settlement from [[shanty town]]s to [[gated community]] coexist in them close to each other.<ref>{{Citation |author=Cairns |title=Troubling Real-estate |year=2002 |page=118}}</ref>

Outside South East Asia, areas with comparable features have been described in China,<ref>{{Citation |author=Guldin |title=Desakotas and Beyond |year=1997 |pages=48, 62}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |first1=Daniel Z. |last1=Sui |first2=Hui |last2=Zeng |title=Modeling the dynamics of landscape structure in Asia’s emerging desakota regions: A case study in Shenzhen |journal=Landscape and Urban Planning |volume=53 |issue=1–4 |year=2001 |pages=37–52 |doi=10.1016/s0169-2046(00)00136-5}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |first1=Yichun |last1=Xie |first2=Michael |last2=Batty |authorlink2=Michael Batty |first3=Kang |last3=Zhao |title=Simulating Emergent Urban Form: Desakota in China |series=CASA Working Paper |number=95 |publisher=Centre for Advanced Spatial Analysis, University College London |url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1267/1/paper95.pdf}}</ref> India, Japan, Taiwan,<ref>{{Cite journal |first1=C.S. |last1=Stone |first2=Chang-Liang |last2=Chi |title=Contesting Urban and Rural Space in Desakota Regions of Taiwan — A Case Study of I-Lan County |journal=[[Environment and Urbanization ASIA]] |year=2012 |volume=3 |number=1 |pages=93–120 |doi=10.1177/097542531200300106}}</ref> and South Korea.<ref>{{Citation |author=Hebbert |title=''Sen-biki'' amidst ''Desakota'' |year=1994 |page=71}}</ref>

