{{Infobox person | name = Hyozo Omori | image = Hyozo Omori 1907.png | image_size = | caption = in 1907 | birth_name = | birth_date = March 14, 1876 | birth_place = Japan | death_date = January 3, 1913 | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | employer = | occupation = | title = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = [[Annie Shepley Omori]] | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = | nationality = Japan }} {{Nihongo|'''Hyozo Omori'''|大森 兵蔵|Ōmori Hyōzō|March 14, 1876 – January 3, 1913}} was a Japanese physical education specialist who studied in America and married the American artist [[Annie Shepley Omori|Annie Barrows Shepley]]. In Japan, they established ''Yurin En'' (House of the Friendly Neighbor), which was a settlement house and leader in the Japanese playground movement. Omori introduced basketball and volleyball to the country and was the team manager at the [[1912 Summer Olympics|1912 Stockholm Olympics]] in Sweden.
==Education== Hyozo Omori was in the 1905 class of [[Stanford University]]{{r|Stanford}} and then continued his studies in Springfield, Massachusetts as a YMCA exchange student.{{r|Basketball}} He graduated from YMCA's College in Springfield{{r|Japan at Olympics}} with honors in 1907.{{r|Am Gym}}
==Marriage and career== In October 1907, Omori married artist [[Annie Shepley Omori|Annie Barrows Shepley]].{{r|ws}} In 1908, when he had returned to Japan, he introduced volleyball and basketball to the country{{r|Basketball}}{{r|Japan at Olympics}} and became known as the "Father of Japanese Basketball".{{r|Better late}} In Tokyo, the Omoris established a [[settlement movement|settlement house]], ''Yurin En'' (House of the Friendly Neighbor) which offered dramatic classes and a playground for children. It also offered courses in sewing, flower arranging, cooking, and crafts as well as mother's meetings and opportunities for people to speak English.{{r|Jordan}}{{r|Survey}} Initially, they met resistance because of their co-educational programs, the fact that the Omoris were Christian, and that they broke down well-establish class barriers.{{r|Jordan}} The ''Yurin En'' was at the forefront of the Japanese playground movement.{{r|Japan at Olympics}}{{r|NRA}}
In 1909, Omori was the Physical Director for the Japanese Association. That year, he wrote "A Brief Survey of the Present Conditions of Physical Education in Japan" for ''Hygiene and Physical Education''.{{r|Hastings}}
Hyozo Omori was a physical education specialist and team manager for the Japanese team that competed in the [[1912 Summer Olympics|1912 Stockholm Olympics]] in Sweden. [[Yahiko Mishima]] from Tokyo Imperial University (now University of Tokyo) ran short distances and [[Shizo Kanakuri]], a 20-year-old Tokyo Higher Normal School student ran the marathon. Judo master [[Kanō Jigorō]] was the leader of the team. It was the first time that Japanese runners competed in the Olympics. Omori became quite ill when the group arrived in Stockholm following the [[Trans-Siberian Railway]] trip.{{r|Better late}}
Hyozo Omori died in 1913, and Annie continued running ''Yurin En'' after his death.{{r|Jordan}}{{r|NRA}}
